I do kind of think that part of the job of the=C2=A0chief executive officer=
 of a bank is that, when there is a run on your bank, you have to go on tel=
evision and say confidently=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyes, everything is fine, our asse=
ts are great and the bank run has stopped.=E2=80=9D If this is true =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if your assets are great and the run has stopped =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
en, you know, great. If it is not true =E2=80=94=C2=A0if your assets are tr=
oubled and the run is ongoing =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, well, that=E2=80=99s why=
 they pay you the big bucks.=C2=A0If you go on television and=C2=A0say=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cyeah turns out our assets are mostly trash and people are pulli=
ng out their money as fast as they can,=E2=80=9D then that is definitely th=
e end of your bank: After you say that, the run will intensify and you=E2=
=80=99ll be broke in an hour. If you go on television and say =E2=80=9Cever=
ything is great,=E2=80=9D and you are confident and poised enough, maybe th=
e run will stop and you=E2=80=99ll have time to actually get back to normal=
.=C2=A0This stuff is not entirely self-fulfilling =E2=80=94=C2=A0lots of ba=
nkers go on TV and say =E2=80=9Ceverything is great=E2=80=9D and the run in=
tensifies anyway and they go bankrupt =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is partially=C2=
=A0self-fulfilling, and your job as CEO really is to stop the run from inte=
nsifying.
